<!-- S4: ILIAD SPOTLIGHT -->
<section class="iliad-spot course-homer" id="iliad">
  
<div class="iliad-book featured-art-panel">
  <img src="/homer.jpg" alt="Homer portrait" class="featured-art-img">
  <div class="featured-art-caption">Homer · Iliad</div>
</div>

  <div class="iliad-content">
    <div class="iliad-tag">Now Enrolling · Q2 2026</div>
    <h2 class="iliad-hed">Homer's<br><em>Iliad</em></h2>
    <div class="iliad-sub">Translated by E.V. Rieu · Instructor: Nick Rosado</div>
    <p class="iliad-desc">The <em>Iliad</em> is not a poem primarily about war. It is a poem fundamentally about life and what makes it worth living — captured in grief, triumph, and in the choices that cannot be unmade. Homer's great insight is that his heroes know this, and choose glory anyway. We will sit with their choices for two and a half months.<br><br>Each week: a pre-recorded lecture to prepare and unpack the reading, a live one-hour session to discuss it together and the kind of close attention to the text that most readers never get. All sessions are recorded. Asynchronous enrollment is available.</p>
    <div class="iliad-grid">
      <div class="iliad-det"><span class="lbl">Duration</span><span class="val">2½ months</span></div>
      <div class="iliad-det"><span class="lbl">Format</span><span class="val">Weekly Live + Async</span></div>
      <div class="iliad-det"><span class="lbl">Sessions</span><span class="val">11 Classes</span></div>
      <div class="iliad-det"><span class="lbl">Price</span><span class="val">$250</span></div>
    </div>
    <div class="iliad-btns">
      <a href="mailto:Unshelledcoast@gmail.com" class="btn-gold">Enroll in This Course</a>
      <a href="mailto:Unshelledcoast@gmail.com" class="btn-ghost">Contact Nick</a>
    </div>
    <div class="accords">
      <div class="accord">
        <button class="accord-btn" onclick="tog(this)"><span class="accord-label"><span class="accord-kicker">Course Overview</span><span class="accord-title">Format & Expectations</span></span><span class="accord-icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="accord-body"><div class="accord-body-inner"><ul>
          <li>11 weekly live sessions, one hour each</li>
          <li>Pre-recorded lectures for every Book, split into pre-reading and post-reading sections</li>
          <li>Required text: <em>Iliad</em>, translated by E.V. Rieu</li>
          <li>~2–3 hours of total weekly commitment (lecture + reading + session)</li>
          <li>All sessions recorded and shared via private link with passcode</li>
          <li>Full asynchronous option available</li>
        </ul></div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="accord">
        <button class="accord-btn" onclick="tog(this)"><span class="accord-label"><span class="accord-kicker">Course Method</span><span class="accord-title">How the Lectures Work</span></span><span class="accord-icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="accord-body"><div class="accord-body-inner">Each pre-recorded lecture has two parts. Before you read, you listen to the introduction — essential context, background and what to look for. After you read, you return for the integrations section, which draws on copious poetic research and connects the Book to broader themes.<br><br>Recommended order: Introduction → Read the Book → Integrations.</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="accord">
        <button class="accord-btn" onclick="tog(this)"><span class="accord-label"><span class="accord-kicker">Weekly Work</span><span class="accord-title">Recurring Assignments</span></span><span class="accord-icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="accord-body"><div class="accord-body-inner"><ul>
          <li><strong style="color:var(--warm)">Weekly line selection:</strong> Each student chooses one line or short passage — one they love, hate or have a question about — and shares it during class with a brief explanation.</li>
          <li><strong style="color:var(--warm)">Plot summary:</strong> Two or three students per week each write a ~seven-sentence summary for one assigned Book, shared at the start of discussion.</li>
        </ul></div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="accord">
        <button class="accord-btn" onclick="tog(this)"><span class="accord-label"><span class="accord-kicker">Live Sessions</span><span class="accord-title">Class Structure</span></span><span class="accord-icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="accord-body"><div class="accord-body-inner">Each Book gets the same three-part structure: (1) Student's short plot summary, (2) Instructor's one to two thematic focus points from the lecture, (3) All students' line selections and open discussion. After class, students have open access to the instructor for further questions.</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="accord">
        <button class="accord-btn" onclick="tog(this)"><span class="accord-label"><span class="accord-kicker">Part I</span><span class="accord-title">Class 1: Orientation & Trojan War Context</span></span><span class="accord-icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="accord-body"><div class="accord-body-inner"><strong style="color:var(--warm)">Pre-Class Viewing:</strong> <em>The Trojan War Cycle</em> (6 min) · <em>Greek Gods Explained in 12 Minutes</em> · Optional: <em>Epic Cycle — The Lost Tales</em> (12 min) · Optional film: <em>Troy</em> (2003)<br><br><strong style="color:var(--warm)">During Class:</strong> Introduction to the epic poetry tradition, Homer's biography and historical context, the Trojan War cycle and key philosophical concepts in the <em>Iliad</em>.</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="accord">
        <button class="accord-btn" onclick="tog(this)"><span class="accord-label"><span class="accord-kicker">Part II</span><span class="accord-title">Classes 2–11: Book-by-Book</span></span><span class="accord-icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="accord-body"><div class="accord-body-inner">Each subsequent class covers two (sometimes three) Books of the <em>Iliad</em> (Books 1–24 across 11 sessions). Pre-class work includes the pre-recorded lecture and reading assignment. During class: student summaries, instructor's thematic focus, and group line discussion.</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

